before I was born. And then my father took over the 
brewery and various uncles. My father was the main

23:32.902 --> 23:36.105
man in running the brewery. And he, my father, 
thought I was, regarded me as totally

23:37.366 --> 23:44.912
impractical. And for many years was exceedingly 
worried lest I shouldn't be able to earn my living.

23:51.993 --> 23:58.540
when I was a boy at school that I should become 
qualified as a chartered accountant, and then go

23:51.993 --> 23:58.540
as an accountant into the brewery. And I remember 
him giving me some small sum of money, investing it

23:59.381 --> 24:05.047
for me. He produced an income of about £100 a year. 
And he said, at any rate, Edward, every day of your

24:08.590 --> 24:14.256
life, you'll be able to buy yourself lunch. Little 
did he know about inflation. And this was a very

24:17.238 --> 24:20.423
curious thing. There was really no reason to 
suppose I couldn't look after my son. If I had been,

24:23.107 --> 24:27.935
as a small child, as I said yesterday, I'd been 
disturbed when I was 10. But he never realized I'd

24:28.756 --> 24:30.799
grown up, I don't think. And so I never had any 
connection with the brewery as long as he was

24:31.541 --> 24:36.228
alive, really. I knew my way around it. I used to go 
down with him as a child. He was very kind to me.

24:40.735 --> 24:42.638
Every Saturday morning I used to go down and meet 
him at the brewery and we'd go around and make the

24:42.955 --> 24:51.708
measurements of the density of the beer or the 
hydromaton and look around and see that

24:42.955 --> 24:51.708
everything was clean and tidy. And then, when he 
died, we found the brewery in quite a mess in the

24:52.509 --> 25:03.866
sense that my father believed that money was bad 
for people. In particular, it was bad for the

25:03.886 --> 25:05.688
shareholders. And therefore he distributed the 
minimum possible amount in dividends And it

25:11.170 --> 25:13.353
stepped the money away. So there was a very large 
collection of cash. And the company was a public

25:17.438 --> 25:19.140
company. And you could buy the shares on the stock 
market. He'd been forced to make it a public

25:21.783 --> 25:29.392
company because he got into trouble with the 
taxation people who insisted on making it a public

25:21.783 --> 25:29.392
company. And if you'd bought the shares on the 
stock market and got control, you'd have found

25:30.113 --> 25:35.279
enough money to pay for them. And my cousin and I 
were very disturbed about this. My cousin asked me

25:38.403 --> 25:40.165
to become a director. And the rest of the directors 
were employees of the company. So in effect, what

25:43.079 --> 25:49.725
my cousin and I said went, because we could just 
have removed the other directors if necessary. So

25:49.745 --> 25:51.026
we ran this thing. My cousin ran it really, and I 
used to go pretty frequently. And we started

25:54.630 --> 25:57.732
buying other breweries with this money. We bought 
the breweries, and we closed them down, and kept

25:58.313 --> 26:02.857
their pubs. So we had more and more pubs. And this 
was going splendidly. We were all making our

26:07.481 --> 26:09.763
fortunes. Suddenly one day we found that Watkins, 
one of the big national brewers, were buying our

26:10.486 --> 26:15.531
shares. And we became rather disturbed about 
this, and eventually they came out into the open

26:16.792 --> 26:23.858
and said they wished to buy the thing. And the price 
they offered was so high that it was clear that a lot

26:23.878 --> 26:34.267
of the shares were held by trustees for old ladies 
in the older generation of the family. And the

26:34.287 --> 26:38.451
trustees would certainly have sold the shares at 
the price that was offered, which was ludicrous.

26:39.055 --> 26:50.348
And so we very regretfully accepted, I think, £9.2 
million for an enterprise that could have been

26:39.055 --> 26:50.348
bought for £1.5 million three or four years 
before. So we did extremely well out of it, but I

26:51.229 --> 26:54.492
very much regretted it. It's certainly been not in 
the public interest and not in our interest. We

26:58.817 --> 27:01.120
could have made more money by going on as we were. We 
had other views for gobbling up other breweries.

27:05.024 --> 27:06.866
And we were doing very well. And what's the public 
is? It's given them no choice between their beers.

27:10.998 --> 27:13.902
They have to drink Mr. Watney's beer now. And it 
didn't do the Watneys much good. Of course, Mr.

27:16.226 --> 27:21.253
Watney paid so much for the thing that they got into 
financial difficulties. And the next takeover

27:21.273 --> 27:24.478
they tried to do failed. And then they got caught 
themselves by a purely financial group. And this

27:29.705 --> 27:33.892
group paid so much for Watneys that they're now in 
financial difficulties. So everyone concerned

27:33.912 --> 27:36.315
is in financial difficulties. except the 
shareholders of the company of Bullards and the

27:36.751 --> 27:42.638
companies we took over. Of course, the people who 
were in the shares of some of the breweries we took

27:43.098 --> 27:52.529
over have been taken over three times, once by us, 
once by Watney's, and once by these financiers.

27:52.549 --> 27:57.995
And they've gained factors varying between 2 and 
10 every time. So a very curious story. But that's

28:00.798 --> 28:04.142
how I became to be in the brewing business. I was a 
consultant to Watney's afterwards. It was all

28:08.295 --> 28:10.079
done quite amiably. And now I have a pension from 
Watney's. Not very much, but I do get a pension from

28:14.471 --> 28:19.043
Watney's.

